SIMPLE: tinsel
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tinsel
<hw>Tin"sel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tincelle</ets> a spark, OF. <ets>estincelle</ets>, L.
<ets>scintilla</ets>. Cf. <er>Scintillate</er>, <er>Stencil</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A shining material used for ornamental purposes;
especially, a very thin, gauzelike cloth with much gold or silver woven
into it; also, very thin metal overlaid with a thin coating of gold or
silver, brass foil, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who can discern the <qex>tinsel</qex> from the gold?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something shining and gaudy; something superficially
shining and showy, or having a false luster, and more gay than
valuable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O happy peasant! O unhappy bard!⟦br⟧
His the mere <qex>tinsel</qex>, hers the rich reward.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinsel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tinsel
<hw>Tin"sel</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Showy to excess; gaudy; specious;
superficial.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Tinsel</xex> trappings.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinsel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tinsel
<hw>Tin"sel</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tinseled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Tinselled</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Tinseling</conjf> or
<conjf>Tinselling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To adorn with tinsel; to deck
out with cheap but showy ornaments; to make gaudy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She, <qex>tinseled</qex> o'er in robes of varying hues.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tinselly</ent>⟦br⟧
